            <p facs="#facs_131_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>[600]
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>is the general presupposition of this whole year of lectures--often tried to rule <rs type="keyword" ref="#Culture">culture</rs> in a heteronomous
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>way, namely by ecclesiastical laws coming from outside and justified in the name of a divine revelation.
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>This is against the structure of man and his <rs type="keyword" ref="#Predicament">predicament</rs>. Against this, therefore, the other side has always
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>arisen, often very much underground, if the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Heteronomy">heteronomy </rs>of the <church>churches</church> was strong enough to keep it
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>down, sometimes open and victoriously, as in the ancient world and in the modern world.
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>Then <rs type="keyword" ref="#Autonomy">autonomy</rs> has arisen, in all cultural realms, in opposition to heteronomy. And something of
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_8" n="N008"/>this, we all have experienced. When we first started thinking and some laws of <rs type="keyword" ref="#Authority">authority</rs> which were not
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_9" n="N009"/>the laws of our OWN being were ruling us, we came into the conflict between autonomy and heteronom [sic.]
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_10" n="N010"/>through which almost every child and adolescent has to go. These conflicts are often terribly hard because
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_11" n="N011"/>the heteronomy is tied up with the highest object of<rs type="keyword" ref="#Love"> love</rs>, be it directly divine, be it representing the divine
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_12" n="N012"/>([such] as parents, or ministers, or friends). And one HAS TO BREAK with them in the moment
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_13" n="N013"/>in which one starts to think autonomously, because the nature of autonomous thinking is the
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_14" n="N014"/>question--questioning everything--the radical doubt.
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_15" n="N015"/><rs type="keyword" ref="#History">History</rs>, especially modern history, has repeated this <rs type="keyword" ref="#Individual">individual </rs>scheme in a complete way.
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_16" n="N016"/>The fight between the <church>churches</church> and modern autonomous <rs type="keyword" ref="#Culture">culture</rs> is going on, even in the <rs type="keyword" ref="#Middle_Ages">Middle Ages</rs>,
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_17" n="N017"/>and certainly in the modern time, and has produced martyrs on both sides--whoever was more powerful.
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_19" n="N018"/>Even today, such conflicts (and they are real) between <rs type="keyword" ref="#Theology">theological</rs> faculties and the other
               <lb facs="#facs_131_tr_3_tl_20" n="N019"/>faculties, reflect this fundamental problem of human existence.
